00:03:07.170 --> 00:03:09.280
So I'll talk about that, OK?

00:03:09.280 --> 00:03:12.030
So are we good?

00:03:12.030 --> 00:03:15.540
So this is a schematic
of articular cartilage.

00:03:15.540 --> 00:03:17.990
Articular just means it's
in a joint, so between

00:03:17.990 --> 00:03:20.410
like, say, two of
your long bones,

00:03:20.410 --> 00:03:21.650
and there's several regions.

00:03:21.650 --> 00:03:25.030
So this shows both the cartilage
and the bone underneath it.

00:03:25.030 --> 00:03:28.930
And so this top layer is
called the superficial layer,

00:03:28.930 --> 00:03:30.410
and then there's
a transition zone,

00:03:30.410 --> 00:03:32.590
and then there's this
deep cartilage here.

00:03:32.590 --> 00:03:36.040
And the little white lines
represent how the collagen

00:03:36.040 --> 00:03:38.540
is oriented in the cartilage.

00:03:38.540 --> 00:03:40.380
So the collagen is
oriented, more or less,

00:03:40.380 --> 00:03:43.610
vertically here and then it
becomes more kind of woven

00:03:43.610 --> 00:03:45.940
and horizontal towards the top.

00:03:45.940 --> 00:03:48.430
And so those three
different zones,

00:03:48.430 --> 00:03:50.670
the collagen is
oriented differently.

00:03:50.670 --> 00:03:54.080
Then there's a region down
here called the tidemark.

00:03:54.080 --> 00:03:58.140
Everything above here is just
cartilage and everything below

00:03:58.140 --> 00:04:00.430
is calcified to some extent.

00:04:00.430 --> 00:04:04.780
So this next layer down here
it's more cartilage-like,

00:04:04.780 --> 00:04:09.300
but it's got some
calcification in it as well.

00:04:09.300 --> 00:04:10.900
And then here's
the compact bone.

00:04:10.900 --> 00:04:12.540
They call it subchondral bone.

00:04:12.540 --> 00:04:14.290
It's the bone below
the cartilage.

00:04:14.290 --> 00:04:15.890
So chondral is cartilage.

00:04:15.890 --> 00:04:17.390
And then here's the
trabecular bone.

00:04:17.390 --> 00:04:22.019
We talked about trabecular
bone a couple of weeks ago, OK?

00:04:22.019 --> 00:04:24.540
So one of the things is there's
different types of collagen

00:04:24.540 --> 00:04:27.900
and the different types may
have slightly different fiber

00:04:27.900 --> 00:04:31.774
structures or slightly
different compositions.

00:04:31.774 --> 00:04:34.190
They're all related, but they're
slightly different types.

00:04:34.190 --> 00:04:36.870
And bone has what's called
type I collagen and cartilage

00:04:36.870 --> 00:04:39.460
has type II collagen. So
when we made the scaffold,

00:04:39.460 --> 00:04:41.350
we wanted the bony
layer to be made

00:04:41.350 --> 00:04:45.140
with type I and the cartilage
layer to be made with type II.

00:04:45.140 --> 00:04:47.870
So I think with the 3032
people have probably seen it.

00:04:47.870 --> 00:04:49.640
I think I did a
version of this for you

00:04:49.640 --> 00:04:52.060
guys, didn't I at the
end of term, something?

00:04:52.060 --> 00:04:56.910
Yeah, but there's other people,
so it's really for them.

00:04:56.910 --> 00:05:02.040
So if you think of
articular cartilage,

00:05:02.040 --> 00:05:05.289
it has difficulty repairing
itself and one of the reasons

00:05:05.289 --> 00:05:06.830
that it's difficult
for the cartilage

00:05:06.830 --> 00:05:10.340
to repair itself is that
there's no blood supply in it

00:05:10.340 --> 00:05:14.160
and another reason is that
there's not very many cells.

00:05:14.160 --> 00:05:17.080
So chondrocytes are
the cells in cartilage

00:05:17.080 --> 00:05:19.450
and if there's a low volume
fraction of the cells,

00:05:19.450 --> 00:05:21.860
then it's not so easy for
that small number of cells

00:05:21.860 --> 00:05:24.760
to actually produce the
extracellular matrix, which

00:05:24.760 --> 00:05:26.740
is kind of what you think
of as the cartilage.

00:05:26.740 --> 00:05:29.745
And it can be damaged, either
as I said, from sports injuries,

00:05:29.745 --> 00:05:31.370
typically that's what
young people get,

00:05:31.370 --> 00:05:34.930
they tear their cartilage in
some sporting injury accident,

00:05:34.930 --> 00:05:36.500
or from osteoarthritis.

00:05:36.500 --> 00:05:38.180
So these scaffolds
we're talking about,

00:05:38.180 --> 00:05:41.080
they're not really meant
to repair large amounts

00:05:41.080 --> 00:05:43.780
of cartilage that are damaged.

00:05:43.780 --> 00:05:46.020
And as I said, the cartilage
has a poor capacity

00:05:46.020 --> 00:05:48.097
for self-repair.

00:05:48.097 --> 00:05:49.680
So there's several
treatments, there's

00:05:49.680 --> 00:05:52.190
three treatments that
are given currently

00:05:52.190 --> 00:05:55.225
and the most common one is
called marrow stimulation.

00:05:55.225 --> 00:05:56.850
And some of these
orthopedic treatments

00:05:56.850 --> 00:05:59.490
are fairly crude
when you look at it.

00:05:59.490 --> 00:06:02.480
So this marrow stimulation,
what's involved

00:06:02.480 --> 00:06:03.390
is they take a drill.

00:06:03.390 --> 00:06:04.302
So here's the drill.

00:06:04.302 --> 00:06:06.260
And they basically drill
through the cartilage.

00:06:06.260 --> 00:06:08.116
So this would be the
cartilage layer here.

00:06:08.116 --> 00:06:09.490
And they drill
down into the bone

00:06:09.490 --> 00:06:11.615
and they want to get down
into the trabecular bone.

00:06:11.615 --> 00:06:13.250
So they want to go
below the cortical

00:06:13.250 --> 00:06:15.250
or the subchondral bone
and they want to go down

00:06:15.250 --> 00:06:17.674
into the trabecular bone.

00:06:17.674 --> 00:06:20.090
And the reason they want to
do that is the trabecular bone

00:06:20.090 --> 00:06:21.910
has bone marrow in it
and the bone marrow

00:06:21.910 --> 00:06:23.860
has mesenchymal
stem cells, and they

00:06:23.860 --> 00:06:26.100
want those mesenchymal
stem cells to move up

00:06:26.100 --> 00:06:27.670
into the cartilage layer.

00:06:27.670 --> 00:06:29.830
So that's what this
red glob is here.

00:06:29.830 --> 00:06:31.900
The idea is that
you've made a hole

00:06:31.900 --> 00:06:33.780
and now that hole
is going to fill up

00:06:33.780 --> 00:06:36.350
with a blood clot, which will
have these mesenchymal stem

00:06:36.350 --> 00:06:40.900
cells, and that those
will form cartilage.

00:06:40.900 --> 00:06:45.900
So it does work to some
extent, but it's not really

00:06:45.900 --> 00:06:49.430
a great result. There's
something like 75,000

00:06:49.430 --> 00:06:50.390
of these done a year.

00:06:50.390 --> 00:06:54.590
As I said, this is the
most common kind of repair.

00:06:54.590 --> 00:06:58.580
The next most sophisticated
type of repair, what they do

00:06:58.580 --> 00:07:01.650
is they take plugs of bone and
cartilage from another place.

00:07:01.650 --> 00:07:03.080
So say this is
where the defect is

00:07:03.080 --> 00:07:04.660
and they want to repair that.

00:07:04.660 --> 00:07:07.240
They take bone and cartilage
from this spot up here.

00:07:07.240 --> 00:07:10.040
So they sort of drill out
little cylindrical cores

00:07:10.040 --> 00:07:12.510
and then they plug them
into this bit here.

00:07:12.510 --> 00:07:15.380
And that's called an
osteochondral autograft.

00:07:15.380 --> 00:07:17.550
Sometimes it's
called mosaicplasty

00:07:17.550 --> 00:07:19.826
because they build up a
little mosaic from all

00:07:19.826 --> 00:07:22.179
those little pieces.

00:07:22.179 --> 00:07:23.970
And then they just
leave these donor sites,

00:07:23.970 --> 00:07:26.550
where they took the plugs from,
they just leave those empty.

00:07:26.550 --> 00:07:30.650
So they try to take the bone
and cartilage from regions where

00:07:30.650 --> 00:07:32.770
the loads are lower,
but they end up

00:07:32.770 --> 00:07:35.990
leaving holes, which
is not so desirable.

00:07:35.990 --> 00:07:38.370
And again, those holes
may fill a little bit

00:07:38.370 --> 00:07:42.600
by the previous mechanism.

00:07:42.600 --> 00:07:45.820
Then the most fancy
method that they use now

00:07:45.820 --> 00:07:48.860
is called autologous
chondrocyte implantation.

00:07:48.860 --> 00:07:51.020
So what they do is they
harvest cartilage cells

00:07:51.020 --> 00:07:52.670
from the patient.

00:07:52.670 --> 00:07:55.040
They then take them to a
lab and they culture them

00:07:55.040 --> 00:07:56.560
for two or three
weeks and they get

00:07:56.560 --> 00:07:59.370
them to multiply and
proliferate and grow

00:07:59.370 --> 00:08:01.890
and then they
re-implant the cells.

00:08:01.890 --> 00:08:05.930
So this works fairly
well, but the difficulty

00:08:05.930 --> 00:08:09.090
is it involves two surgeries,
so one to get the cells out

00:08:09.090 --> 00:08:11.190
and one to put them
back in, and there's

00:08:11.190 --> 00:08:12.619
the cost of the cell culture.

00:08:12.619 --> 00:08:15.160
So this is a much more expensive
procedure because of the two

00:08:15.160 --> 00:08:18.340
surgeries and the cost of
doing the cell culture,

00:08:18.340 --> 00:08:21.010
but I think it's the
method that works the best.

00:08:21.010 --> 00:08:25.550
And when I talked about this in
3032, I mentioned Dara Torres.

00:08:25.550 --> 00:08:27.670
Dara Torres is an
Olympic swimmer.

00:08:27.670 --> 00:08:29.134
She's 47.

00:08:29.134 --> 00:08:30.550
She began swimming
in the Olympics

00:08:30.550 --> 00:08:33.370
in 1984, more than 30 years ago.

00:08:33.370 --> 00:08:35.039
And she has swum
in the Olympics,

00:08:35.039 --> 00:08:37.750
not every one,
but up until 2008.

00:08:37.750 --> 00:08:40.669
And even 2008, she won
three silvers that year.

00:08:40.669 --> 00:08:42.299
She was, I think,
the oldest person

00:08:42.299 --> 00:08:44.740
who's ever won a
medal in the Olympics.

00:08:44.740 --> 00:08:49.420
And she had this surgery done
at the Brigham a few years ago.

00:08:49.420 --> 00:08:51.054
And it used to be,
they've stopped

00:08:51.054 --> 00:08:53.220
running these commercials
but the Brigham for a time

00:08:53.220 --> 00:08:56.070
was running these commercials,
that featured Dara Torres

00:08:56.070 --> 00:09:00.270
and saying basically that she
had this surgery done there.

00:09:00.270 --> 00:09:03.180
I'm assuming she
was happy with it.

00:09:03.180 --> 00:09:05.526
OK, so that's what
they do currently

00:09:05.526 --> 00:09:08.150
and what we were thinking of and
what other groups have thought

00:09:08.150 --> 00:09:12.480
about is could you repair
damage in the cartilage

00:09:12.480 --> 00:09:14.860
by using a tissue
engineering scaffold?

00:09:14.860 --> 00:09:16.360
So what we were
thinking about when

00:09:16.360 --> 00:09:19.750
we tried to do
this project was we

00:09:19.750 --> 00:09:23.130
wanted to use a healthy
articular cartilage joint

00:09:23.130 --> 00:09:25.740
as a model for our scaffold.

00:09:25.740 --> 00:09:29.260
We wanted to have a layer that
would go down into the bone

00:09:29.260 --> 00:09:32.100
so that you would have access
to those mesenchymal stem cells.

00:09:32.100 --> 00:09:34.780
And that's why we wanted
an osteochondral scaffold,

00:09:34.780 --> 00:09:37.190
so that we would have a
layer for the cartilage

00:09:37.190 --> 00:09:39.730
but also a layer that would
go down into the bone.

00:09:39.730 --> 00:09:42.810
We wanted to be able to control
scaffold parameters, things

00:09:42.810 --> 00:09:45.460
like the mineral content
and the pore size.

00:09:45.460 --> 00:09:47.970
Remember, I said these
tissue engineering scaffolds,

00:09:47.970 --> 00:09:49.750
the pore size is one
of the parameters,

00:09:49.750 --> 00:09:53.080
that you want to have the
pore size in a certain range.

00:09:53.080 --> 00:09:54.700
And we wanted to
use materials that

00:09:54.700 --> 00:09:57.990
would be appropriate
for approval

00:09:57.990 --> 00:09:59.711
from things like the FDA.

00:09:59.711 --> 00:10:02.210
So typically, when people make
tissue engineering scaffolds,

00:10:02.210 --> 00:10:03.660
they don't start with
some material that's

00:10:03.660 --> 00:10:04.650
never been approved before.

00:10:04.650 --> 00:10:05.800
They start with
something that already

00:10:05.800 --> 00:10:07.550
has approval for
something else and that's

00:10:07.550 --> 00:10:09.440
what we wanted to do too.

00:10:09.440 --> 00:10:12.500
So this was our idea of
what we wanted the scaffold

00:10:12.500 --> 00:10:13.100
to look like.

00:10:13.100 --> 00:10:16.380
We wanted an unmineralized type
II collagen scaffold up here

00:10:16.380 --> 00:10:17.880
that would be for the cartilage.

00:10:17.880 --> 00:10:20.900
We wanted a mineralized type
I collagen scaffold down there

00:10:20.900 --> 00:10:22.300
for the bone.

00:10:22.300 --> 00:10:23.750
And we wanted some
region that had

00:10:23.750 --> 00:10:26.150
some gradient in
mineralization because it

00:10:26.150 --> 00:10:28.309
would be like that
layer of cartilage that

00:10:28.309 --> 00:10:29.350
was slightly mineralized.

00:10:29.350 --> 00:10:31.920
So we wanted to duplicate
that whole structure.

00:10:31.920 --> 00:10:34.384
So that was our picture
of what we wanted to do

00:10:34.384 --> 00:10:37.050
and we had a pretty good idea of
how we were going to make this.

00:10:37.050 --> 00:10:38.841
We were just going to
use that same process

00:10:38.841 --> 00:10:41.540
that [INAUDIBLE] developed
for the skin scaffolds.

00:10:41.540 --> 00:10:43.000
He was involved
with this project

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:45.760
but just used type II
collagen instead of type I.

00:10:45.760 --> 00:10:47.730
The challenge was
really figuring out

00:10:47.730 --> 00:10:50.820
how to make the mineralized
collagen scaffold

00:10:50.820 --> 00:10:54.410
and then how to get this
gradient in the mineralization

00:10:54.410 --> 00:10:56.442
between the two layers.

00:10:56.442 --> 00:10:58.150
So this, I think, I
showed you last time.

00:10:58.150 --> 00:10:59.899
So this is just the
method we used to make

00:10:59.899 --> 00:11:01.220
the collagen-GAG scaffold.

00:11:01.220 --> 00:11:04.290
So we take type II collagen.
We put it in acetic acid.

00:11:04.290 --> 00:11:06.670
Remember, that destroys
the periodic banding

00:11:06.670 --> 00:11:10.880
of the collagen and it improves
the immunological response.

00:11:10.880 --> 00:11:13.440
We add the chondroitin
6-sulfate, the GAG,

00:11:13.440 --> 00:11:14.640
to crosslink it.

00:11:14.640 --> 00:11:16.800
We then just make a
slurry out of that.

00:11:16.800 --> 00:11:18.000
So we mix that all together.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:19.640
We keep it as a slurry.

00:11:19.640 --> 00:11:21.490
And then the second
stage is you put

00:11:21.490 --> 00:11:24.200
the slurry or the
suspension into a pan,

00:11:24.200 --> 00:11:25.970
and then you do the
freeze drying process.

00:11:25.970 --> 00:11:27.469
So you go through
this process where

00:11:27.469 --> 00:11:29.200
you start at this
room temperature

00:11:29.200 --> 00:11:30.660
and atmospheric pressure.

00:11:30.660 --> 00:11:33.290
You cool it down to freeze
it, and then you sublimate it,

00:11:33.290 --> 00:11:38.560
and you're left with a very
porous collagen-GAG scaffold.

00:11:38.560 --> 00:11:39.700
So these are pictures.

00:11:39.700 --> 00:11:41.370
I think this was with
a type I collagen,

00:11:41.370 --> 00:11:44.120
but it looks the same
with the type II collagen.

00:11:44.120 --> 00:11:47.251
So that's what the
structure looks like.

00:11:47.251 --> 00:11:48.750
I think I showed
you this last time.

00:11:48.750 --> 00:11:51.120
We can control the pore
size by controlling

00:11:51.120 --> 00:11:52.540
the freezing temperature.

00:11:52.540 --> 00:11:54.020
So the way the
freeze dryer works

00:11:54.020 --> 00:11:56.880
is there is shelves that
you put these pans on,

00:11:56.880 --> 00:11:59.909
and these cooling elements
go through the shelves,

00:11:59.909 --> 00:12:01.950
and you can set the
temperature of those shelves.

00:12:01.950 --> 00:12:05.300
So we would set the
temperature of those shelves

00:12:05.300 --> 00:12:07.822
to different values and we
got different pore sizes.

00:12:07.822 --> 00:12:09.280
So the colder the
shelf temperature

00:12:09.280 --> 00:12:14.330
was, the faster the
freezing, and the smaller

00:12:14.330 --> 00:12:16.130
the size of the ice
grains, and then

00:12:16.130 --> 00:12:19.010
the smaller the
size of the pores.

00:12:19.010 --> 00:12:21.280
And this is just the
mechanical response again.

00:12:21.280 --> 00:12:23.350
So we did mechanical
tests on it.

00:12:23.350 --> 00:12:26.010
These are some of the
numbers for the properties.

00:12:26.010 --> 00:12:27.900
So we tested it
dry and wet, and we

00:12:27.900 --> 00:12:30.391
measured a modulus and a
buckling collapse stress

00:12:30.391 --> 00:12:30.890
for it.

00:12:30.890 --> 00:12:33.560
So those are just
some values there.

00:12:33.560 --> 00:12:36.440
And then it came to making
the mineralized collagen-GAG

00:12:36.440 --> 00:12:40.250
scaffold, and one of the
students in Cambridge, England

00:12:40.250 --> 00:12:43.937
was really the main person
who did this, Andrew Lynn.

00:12:43.937 --> 00:12:45.520
And he worked with
Brendan Harley, who

00:12:45.520 --> 00:12:48.290
was our student here,
and after they graduated,

00:12:48.290 --> 00:12:49.900
I had another student,
Biraja Kanungo,

00:12:49.900 --> 00:12:51.370
who worked on this too.

00:12:51.370 --> 00:12:53.790
So Andrew Lynn really
developed this technique.

00:12:53.790 --> 00:12:56.260
And this involved taking
the collagen and the GAG, so

00:12:56.260 --> 00:12:58.185
the same as for
the other scaffold,

00:12:58.185 --> 00:13:00.560
but this time, if we want to
make a mineralized scaffold,

00:13:00.560 --> 00:13:02.850
we somehow have to get
calcium phosphate into it.

00:13:02.850 --> 00:13:05.760
So it's got to have sort of
a hydroxyapatite-ish type

00:13:05.760 --> 00:13:07.940
of component to it.

00:13:07.940 --> 00:13:12.180
So this time we used phosphoric
acid instead of the acetic acid

00:13:12.180 --> 00:13:15.680
and we put some calcium salts
into the mixture as well.

00:13:15.680 --> 00:13:18.820
And Andrew was really the one
who figured out how to do this

00:13:18.820 --> 00:13:20.350
and what salts to use.

00:13:20.350 --> 00:13:21.970
And then the process
was very similar.

00:13:21.970 --> 00:13:23.330
So we have this slurry.

00:13:23.330 --> 00:13:24.830
We mix the slurry up.

00:13:24.830 --> 00:13:27.110
We did a freeze drying
process, and then we

00:13:27.110 --> 00:13:29.980
crosslinked it with a chemical
crosslinker called EDAC.

00:13:29.980 --> 00:13:31.950
So it's just a chemical
that you put into this

00:13:31.950 --> 00:13:33.560
and it crosslinks it all.

00:13:33.560 --> 00:13:37.350
So that was how we made
the mineralized scaffold.

00:13:37.350 --> 00:13:39.640
The mineral we got was
something called brushite,

00:13:39.640 --> 00:13:41.890
which is a calcium phosphate,
but it's not exactly

00:13:41.890 --> 00:13:43.840
the same as hydroxyapatite.

00:13:43.840 --> 00:13:46.590
And we could control
the amount of brushite

00:13:46.590 --> 00:13:48.840
by different weight
fractions or volume fractions

00:13:48.840 --> 00:13:51.190
by controlling how much of
the calcium salts we put in

00:13:51.190 --> 00:13:54.630
and what the molarity of
the phosphoric acid was.

00:13:54.630 --> 00:13:56.670
If you take brushite
and you put it in water,

00:13:56.670 --> 00:13:59.040
it then converts to
octacalcium phosphate

00:13:59.040 --> 00:14:01.900
and then to apatite by
a hydrolytic conversion.

00:14:01.900 --> 00:14:06.360
So the apatite is related to
the hydroxyapatite in bone.

00:14:06.360 --> 00:14:08.670
And this was the structure
of the mineralized scaffold

00:14:08.670 --> 00:14:09.610
that we got.

00:14:09.610 --> 00:14:11.360
So you can see it looks
a little different

00:14:11.360 --> 00:14:13.440
from the collagen-GAG scaffold.

00:14:13.440 --> 00:14:14.380
It's much denser.

00:14:14.380 --> 00:14:17.220
Typically, the densities
were like 5% or 10% dense.

00:14:17.220 --> 00:14:19.740
And remember, the collagen
scaffold was 0.5% dense.

00:14:19.740 --> 00:14:21.529
So it's a lot denser.

00:14:21.529 --> 00:14:23.820
But if you notice, there's
a few things to notice here.

00:14:23.820 --> 00:14:27.300
So one is the pore size,
that's a 500 micron bar.

00:14:27.300 --> 00:14:31.000
And we could make pores between
about 50 and 1,000 microns,

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:32.980
depending on the
freezing conditions.

00:14:32.980 --> 00:14:35.190
And the range of pore
sizes we were shooting for

00:14:35.190 --> 00:14:36.860
was somewhere
between 100 and 500,

00:14:36.860 --> 00:14:38.390
so we could get in the
right ballpark with that.

00:14:38.390 --> 00:14:40.306
And you can see, just
looking at that picture,

00:14:40.306 --> 00:14:42.200
if that's 500
microns, those pores

00:14:42.200 --> 00:14:44.400
are somewhere of that order.

00:14:44.400 --> 00:14:47.480
Another thing to look
at is this image here,

00:14:47.480 --> 00:14:50.000
and this just shows,
the white little dots

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:52.500
are the calcium
phosphate mineral,

00:14:52.500 --> 00:14:53.980
and it just shows
that the mineral

00:14:53.980 --> 00:14:56.240
is uniformly distributed
throughout the thickness

00:14:56.240 --> 00:14:57.430
of the scaffold.

00:14:57.430 --> 00:15:00.330
So some people had tried to make
scaffolds for regenerating bone

00:15:00.330 --> 00:15:03.200
where they take, say,
one of those polymers

00:15:03.200 --> 00:15:05.060
for resorbable sutures
or they take collagen

00:15:05.060 --> 00:15:07.460
and they coat it
with hydroxyapatite,

00:15:07.460 --> 00:15:11.230
but the shortcoming of that
is that the scaffold is

00:15:11.230 --> 00:15:12.519
going to resorb over time.

00:15:12.519 --> 00:15:14.810
The cells are going to secrete
enzymes, which are going

00:15:14.810 --> 00:15:16.420
to eat away at the scaffold.

00:15:16.420 --> 00:15:18.350
And if the scaffold
resorbs, you're

00:15:18.350 --> 00:15:20.110
eating away at the
hydroxyapatite first

00:15:20.110 --> 00:15:21.526
and then you're
left with whatever

00:15:21.526 --> 00:15:23.050
polymer is underneath that.

00:15:23.050 --> 00:15:26.032
Whereas this gives you a
more uniform composition

00:15:26.032 --> 00:15:27.740
throughout the thickness
of the scaffold,

00:15:27.740 --> 00:15:29.870
and you've got calcium
phosphate everywhere

00:15:29.870 --> 00:15:32.880
throughout the thickness of
the struts in the scaffold.

00:15:32.880 --> 00:15:35.470
So that's the structure of that.

00:15:35.470 --> 00:15:38.550
We wanted to make sure that
the mineral was uniformly

00:15:38.550 --> 00:15:40.840
distributed throughout
the scaffold,

00:15:40.840 --> 00:15:43.390
and we did some micro-CT
imaging, some micro computer

00:15:43.390 --> 00:15:44.700
tomography.

00:15:44.700 --> 00:15:47.100
And this is our sample
here, and this red line just

00:15:47.100 --> 00:15:51.300
says that is the plane at
which this image was taken,

00:15:51.300 --> 00:15:53.170
and the black is the mineral.

00:15:53.170 --> 00:15:55.640
And then here's a lower plane
and here's another image.

00:15:55.640 --> 00:15:58.540
And you can see the calcium
phosphate's pretty uniformly

00:15:58.540 --> 00:16:02.020
distributed throughout
that specimen there.

00:16:02.020 --> 00:16:05.860
And this was just another way of
looking at the same thing using

00:16:05.860 --> 00:16:08.924
EDX in an SEM to look
at where the calcium was

00:16:08.924 --> 00:16:10.090
and where the phosphate was.

00:16:10.090 --> 00:16:13.830
So again, this is uniform
distribution of the mineral.

00:16:13.830 --> 00:16:16.530
We did mechanical tests
on these scaffold as well.

00:16:16.530 --> 00:16:19.437
So we measured moduli
and collapse stresses.

00:16:19.437 --> 00:16:21.520
We get the same kind of
stress strain curve as all

00:16:21.520 --> 00:16:24.340
these other cellular solids.

00:16:24.340 --> 00:16:26.560
This was done by-
Biraja Kanungo was

00:16:26.560 --> 00:16:29.220
the student who did this bit.

00:16:29.220 --> 00:16:31.590
One of the things
we found was that

00:16:31.590 --> 00:16:33.510
with these mineralized
scaffolds you

00:16:33.510 --> 00:16:35.290
could manually compress them.

00:16:35.290 --> 00:16:38.300
If you pushed them down
and you hydrated them,

00:16:38.300 --> 00:16:40.970
they would recover
all the deformation,

00:16:40.970 --> 00:16:42.730
but we were increased
in improving

00:16:42.730 --> 00:16:45.820
the mechanical properties
of the mineralized scaffold

00:16:45.820 --> 00:16:48.250
for improved handling
during surgery.

00:16:48.250 --> 00:16:51.610
And there's another reason
that I'll get to as well.

00:16:51.610 --> 00:16:54.230
So the second reason
is that, if you

00:16:54.230 --> 00:16:56.140
look at how bone
itself forms, it

00:16:56.140 --> 00:17:01.964
forms from a collagen
precursor, so bone in your body.

00:17:01.964 --> 00:17:03.505
And there's something
called osteoid,

00:17:03.505 --> 00:17:07.470
which is this collagen-based
precursor to bone,

00:17:07.470 --> 00:17:11.569
and it has a modulus of
about 25 to 40 kilopascals

00:17:11.569 --> 00:17:14.880
and Angler showed that if you
have mesenchymal stem cells

00:17:14.880 --> 00:17:17.230
and you put them on substrates
of different stiffnesses,

00:17:17.230 --> 00:17:19.637
they differentiate into
different kinds of cells,

00:17:19.637 --> 00:17:21.470
depending on the stiffness
of the substrate.

00:17:21.470 --> 00:17:23.980
So the substrate stiffness
can affect what kind of cells

00:17:23.980 --> 00:17:25.075
you get.

00:17:25.075 --> 00:17:26.700
And the idea here
was we thought, well,

00:17:26.700 --> 00:17:29.960
if we could get a stiffness that
was close to this osteoid, what

00:17:29.960 --> 00:17:32.620
the natural bone
formation has, then

00:17:32.620 --> 00:17:34.670
that might help the
mesenchymal stem

00:17:34.670 --> 00:17:37.490
cells differentiate
into the bony cells

00:17:37.490 --> 00:17:38.510
that we want them to.

00:17:38.510 --> 00:17:40.700
So we wanted to try to
reach a stiffness of this

00:17:40.700 --> 00:17:42.020
in the wet state.

00:17:42.020 --> 00:17:44.160
And if I back up here,
you can see the stiffness

00:17:44.160 --> 00:17:47.690
we had was around four in the
wet state, four kilopascals

00:17:47.690 --> 00:17:52.040
and we want to get to 30
or 40, something like that.

00:17:52.040 --> 00:17:56.100
So these are our
equations for the modeling

00:17:56.100 --> 00:17:59.370
of the mineralized scaffold,
the open celled foam

00:17:59.370 --> 00:18:02.730
models for the modulus and
for the collapse strength.

00:18:02.730 --> 00:18:04.490
So we could change
different things.

00:18:04.490 --> 00:18:06.054
We could change the
solid properties

00:18:06.054 --> 00:18:07.720
or we could change
the relative density.

00:18:07.720 --> 00:18:09.740
The geometry of the
thing is probably not

00:18:09.740 --> 00:18:11.116
going to help us too much.

00:18:11.116 --> 00:18:12.490
So basically,
that's what we did.

00:18:12.490 --> 00:18:15.879
We first started off trying to
increase the mineral content.

00:18:15.879 --> 00:18:17.920
We thought if there was
more mineral content that

00:18:17.920 --> 00:18:19.160
would make it stiffer.

00:18:19.160 --> 00:18:24.210
So Biraja made these more highly
mineralized scaffolds and these

00:18:24.210 --> 00:18:27.800
are just some SEM
images of those.

00:18:27.800 --> 00:18:30.190
But the thing he found was
that the properties actually

00:18:30.190 --> 00:18:32.840
got worse when he had the more
highly mineralized scaffold.

00:18:32.840 --> 00:18:35.300
The modulus went down and
the strength went down,

00:18:35.300 --> 00:18:37.595
so that wasn't very helpful.

00:18:37.595 --> 00:18:39.220
And when he looked
into it more detail,

00:18:39.220 --> 00:18:41.490
he found that he had more
voids in the cell walls

00:18:41.490 --> 00:18:43.990
and he had more
disconnected walls.

00:18:43.990 --> 00:18:45.980
This shows some of
the micrographs,

00:18:45.980 --> 00:18:48.220
so this isn't really
very quantitative,

00:18:48.220 --> 00:18:49.820
but you can see
there's holes here.

00:18:49.820 --> 00:18:51.320
There's a few holes
here, but there

00:18:51.320 --> 00:18:54.060
tended to be a bigger volume
fraction of holes in the more

00:18:54.060 --> 00:18:57.280
highly mineralized scaffolds
and more walls that

00:18:57.280 --> 00:18:58.520
were disconnected.

00:18:58.520 --> 00:19:00.780
So we realized increasing
the mineral content wasn't

00:19:00.780 --> 00:19:02.204
going to work very well.

00:19:02.204 --> 00:19:03.620
And then the second
thing he tried

00:19:03.620 --> 00:19:05.630
was increasing the
relative density.

00:19:05.630 --> 00:19:10.040
So we started off at this
density of 4 1/2% dense and he

00:19:10.040 --> 00:19:13.320
developed a method of increasing
the relative density up

00:19:13.320 --> 00:19:16.110
to about almost 20% here.

00:19:16.110 --> 00:19:18.090
He did this by, first
of all, he tried

00:19:18.090 --> 00:19:20.280
to just mix more
of the constituents

00:19:20.280 --> 00:19:22.990
into the slurry, that's kind
of the most obvious thing.

00:19:22.990 --> 00:19:24.670
But as you add
more constituents,

00:19:24.670 --> 00:19:27.250
it gets harder and harder
to mix the thing up and have

00:19:27.250 --> 00:19:29.490
it homogeneously distributed.

00:19:29.490 --> 00:19:32.070
So in the end, that's not
how he made these things.

00:19:32.070 --> 00:19:34.240
He started with the
starting mixture

00:19:34.240 --> 00:19:36.970
and then he had a vacuum system
for sucking water out of it.

00:19:36.970 --> 00:19:38.670
So he would reduce
the amount of water,

00:19:38.670 --> 00:19:40.780
which essentially increased
the amount of solids

00:19:40.780 --> 00:19:41.940
that was in there.

00:19:41.940 --> 00:19:44.010
And you can see in
this last one here,

00:19:44.010 --> 00:19:46.530
the most dense
scaffold, he was sucking

00:19:46.530 --> 00:19:48.940
the water in one
direction, and he sucked it

00:19:48.940 --> 00:19:51.420
so much that he was starting
to get the cells collapsing.

00:19:51.420 --> 00:19:54.030
So this one here,
these cells that

00:19:54.030 --> 00:19:56.071
have this sort of elongated
orientation, that's

00:19:56.071 --> 00:19:57.820
because the cells are
starting to collapse

00:19:57.820 --> 00:20:00.301
because of the vacuum
that he was applying.

00:20:00.301 --> 00:20:02.050
But he could get a
pretty good difference.

00:20:02.050 --> 00:20:03.410
This was almost 5%.

00:20:03.410 --> 00:20:06.640
That's almost 20%, so
roughly a factor of four.

00:20:06.640 --> 00:20:09.550
There are, yeah, four
difference between them.

00:20:09.550 --> 00:20:11.320
So then he did
mechanical tests too,

00:20:11.320 --> 00:20:13.660
and he measured the
relative density.

00:20:13.660 --> 00:20:18.240
Here's the moduli wet
and then the strength dry

00:20:18.240 --> 00:20:20.140
and the strength wet.

00:20:20.140 --> 00:20:22.350
So you can see here, if
you look at the dry moduli,

00:20:22.350 --> 00:20:25.280
for instance, when you go
from this relative density

00:20:25.280 --> 00:20:28.970
to that relative density,
from about 14% to 19%,

00:20:28.970 --> 00:20:30.910
the modulus actually drops down.

00:20:30.910 --> 00:20:32.680
And if you look at the
structure, I think,

00:20:32.680 --> 00:20:35.140
it's because you've got this
flattened structure here.

00:20:35.140 --> 00:20:37.720
You've collapsed the
cells a bit already.

00:20:37.720 --> 00:20:39.810
So there's a maximum
density that you

00:20:39.810 --> 00:20:44.510
might want to go to, probably
somewhere around 14% or 15%.

00:20:44.510 --> 00:20:46.510
But the wet modulus
we've got here

00:20:46.510 --> 00:20:50.110
is around 35 kilopascals, so
that's close to the target

00:20:50.110 --> 00:20:50.610
that we had.

00:20:50.610 --> 00:20:52.390
It's close to what
we wanted to have.

00:20:52.390 --> 00:20:53.940
So one way you
could get the right

00:20:53.940 --> 00:20:58.610
or the appropriate modulus
is by increasing the density

00:20:58.610 --> 00:21:00.020
to that value.

00:21:00.020 --> 00:21:02.630
Another way is by playing
around with the crosslinking.

00:21:02.630 --> 00:21:06.020
So those values were for
non-crosslinked scaffolds.

00:21:06.020 --> 00:21:10.720
So here, this is the 14% dense
scaffold wet, non-crosslinked

00:21:10.720 --> 00:21:13.020
it was around 35 kilopascals.

00:21:13.020 --> 00:21:15.370
This is a dehydrothermal
treatment,

00:21:15.370 --> 00:21:17.560
just basically heating it up.

00:21:17.560 --> 00:21:19.650
It gives you a higher modulus.

00:21:19.650 --> 00:21:22.780
And then this is a chemical
crosslinking technique that

00:21:22.780 --> 00:21:24.560
increases the modulus again.

00:21:24.560 --> 00:21:27.090
So if you put all
of this together,

00:21:27.090 --> 00:21:30.930
you can show these results
for the modulus on one table.

00:21:30.930 --> 00:21:32.597
So these are all
the wet modulus.

00:21:32.597 --> 00:21:34.180
So it's pretty clear
by playing around

00:21:34.180 --> 00:21:36.950
with the relative density
and the crosslinking,

00:21:36.950 --> 00:21:39.430
that you can get a
scaffold in that range.

00:21:39.430 --> 00:21:42.580
And the idea is that that would
help get the mesenchymal stem

00:21:42.580 --> 00:21:47.630
cells to differentiate into
these osteoblast-like cells.

00:21:47.630 --> 00:21:49.510
So then we wanted to
also see if our models

00:21:49.510 --> 00:21:54.030
for the cellular solids could
be applied to this scaffold,

00:21:54.030 --> 00:21:56.500
and we needed the
solid properties.

00:21:56.500 --> 00:21:59.910
So Kristyn Van Vliet
helped us with this,

00:21:59.910 --> 00:22:04.932
and we isolated a single strut,
bonded it to a glass slide,

00:22:04.932 --> 00:22:06.640
and, I think, I
mentioned this last time,

00:22:06.640 --> 00:22:10.017
we used an AFM tip to then
do a little bending test.

00:22:10.017 --> 00:22:11.850
So I think the one I
mentioned last time was

00:22:11.850 --> 00:22:13.330
for the collagen-GAG scaffold.

00:22:13.330 --> 00:22:16.340
Then we also did the same thing
for the mineralized scaffold.

00:22:16.340 --> 00:22:20.390
And here we measured a modulus
of about seven gigapascals,

00:22:20.390 --> 00:22:22.010
so that's a dry modulus.

00:22:22.010 --> 00:22:23.650
And just for
comparison, the modulus

00:22:23.650 --> 00:22:26.190
of the solid and trabecular
bone is something around 18.

00:22:26.190 --> 00:22:29.000
So it's lower, but it's
in the same ballpark.

00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:31.890
And by nanoindentation,
we measured a strength

00:22:31.890 --> 00:22:34.800
of about 200, and that's
similar to what you

00:22:34.800 --> 00:22:36.160
would get in trabecular bone.

00:22:36.160 --> 00:22:38.410
So the solid in the
struts themselves

00:22:38.410 --> 00:22:42.230
is not exactly like trabecular
bone in mechanical properties,

00:22:42.230 --> 00:22:44.550
but not too far off.

00:22:44.550 --> 00:22:48.520
And then here's a plot of
the scaffold modulus divided

00:22:48.520 --> 00:22:51.940
by the solid modulus against
the relative density.

00:22:51.940 --> 00:22:56.250
And this line here, the curve,
is a squared relationship.

00:22:56.250 --> 00:22:59.540
So that's what we'd expect
for the foam models.

00:22:59.540 --> 00:23:00.590
And this is the strength.

00:23:00.590 --> 00:23:04.730
These things fail by a
plastic or a brittle failure,

00:23:04.730 --> 00:23:09.741
and this curve is a three halves
power with relative density.

00:23:09.741 --> 00:23:12.240
And again, that's what you'd
expect from the cellular solids

00:23:12.240 --> 00:23:12.740
model.

00:23:12.740 --> 00:23:14.530
So that gives you a
reasonable description

00:23:14.530 --> 00:23:20.040
of the behavior of the
mineralized scaffold.

00:23:20.040 --> 00:23:21.840
So again, these were
the considerations

00:23:21.840 --> 00:23:23.740
in trying to make the
osteochondral scaffold.

00:23:23.740 --> 00:23:25.080
So now we have a
collagen scaffold

00:23:25.080 --> 00:23:26.065
and we have a
mineralized scaffolding,

00:23:26.065 --> 00:23:28.470
and we want to put the
two of them together.

00:23:28.470 --> 00:23:30.970
So we wanted to use
the joint as a model,

00:23:30.970 --> 00:23:33.880
and we wanted to have some
intermediate layer that

00:23:33.880 --> 00:23:36.770
had some gradation in
the mineralization.

00:23:36.770 --> 00:23:38.840
So that was the next step.

00:23:38.840 --> 00:23:41.940
And the way we did
that was we used

00:23:41.940 --> 00:23:45.900
what we fancily called
liquid-phase co-synthesis.

00:23:45.900 --> 00:23:48.490
This just meant that we took
the mineralized collagen-GAG

00:23:48.490 --> 00:23:50.770
slurry, we poured
that into a mold,

00:23:50.770 --> 00:23:53.030
and then we poured the
non-mineralized slurry

00:23:53.030 --> 00:23:54.306
into the same mold.

00:23:54.306 --> 00:23:56.680
And then we just allowed the
two slurries to interdiffuse

00:23:56.680 --> 00:23:58.315
for some time period.

00:23:58.315 --> 00:23:59.940
And then we did the
freeze drying step.

00:23:59.940 --> 00:24:02.450
So the idea was, that if
you poured the one on top

00:24:02.450 --> 00:24:04.899
of the other, the
mineralized one is denser

00:24:04.899 --> 00:24:06.690
and then you put the
less dense one on top,

00:24:06.690 --> 00:24:08.481
but over some period
of time, there will be

00:24:08.481 --> 00:24:10.410
some diffusion between the two.

00:24:10.410 --> 00:24:12.630
And then we just did
the freeze drying step.

00:24:12.630 --> 00:24:14.390
So this is the scaffold
we ended up with.

00:24:14.390 --> 00:24:16.810
This is a micro computer
tomography image.

00:24:16.810 --> 00:24:19.490
So here's the
collagen-GAG scaffold

00:24:19.490 --> 00:24:21.830
for the cartilage
on top, and here's

00:24:21.830 --> 00:24:25.870
the mineralized collagen-GAG
calcium phosphate scaffold

00:24:25.870 --> 00:24:28.060
on the bottom for the bone.

00:24:28.060 --> 00:24:31.920
And that just kind of
shows what it looked like.

00:24:31.920 --> 00:24:33.860
The porosities
and the pore sizes

00:24:33.860 --> 00:24:37.140
we got, the collagen-GAG
was about 98% porous

00:24:37.140 --> 00:24:40.030
and had a pore size
of around 650 microns.

00:24:40.030 --> 00:24:43.250
The mineralized scaffold
was 95.5% porous

00:24:43.250 --> 00:24:48.192
and had a pore size of
400, roughly, microns.

00:24:48.192 --> 00:24:49.650
And then this is
what the structure

00:24:49.650 --> 00:24:51.840
looked like in the EDX.

00:24:51.840 --> 00:24:54.050
You can see, this is
the collagen-GAG layer,

00:24:54.050 --> 00:24:55.800
this is the mineralized
layer, and there's

00:24:55.800 --> 00:24:58.770
some zone in between that's
a little bit mineralized, not

00:24:58.770 --> 00:25:02.330
as much as the bony layer
but more than the cartilage

00:25:02.330 --> 00:25:07.230
layer, and the same
with the phosphorus.

00:25:07.230 --> 00:25:12.390
So we have this collagen-GAG
slightly mineralized layer,

00:25:12.390 --> 00:25:15.550
and then a more
mineralized layer

00:25:15.550 --> 00:25:18.520
And then finally, there was
a student, Scott Vickers,

00:25:18.520 --> 00:25:20.680
who worked with Myron
Spector at the Brigham.

