figures, and mostly it's text,

00:33:11.010 --> 00:33:12.960
but let me go through
some of the figures.

00:33:12.960 --> 00:33:18.110
So I'm going to just turn
to what's page three, OK?

00:33:18.110 --> 00:33:20.890
So one of the things
that he says to start,

00:33:20.890 --> 00:33:22.870
and I think this
makes a lot of sense,

00:33:22.870 --> 00:33:26.236
is that you can think of
writing a paper the same way you

00:33:26.236 --> 00:33:28.360
can think about designing
something in engineering.

00:33:28.360 --> 00:33:30.290
So when you think
about design, there's

00:33:30.290 --> 00:33:31.750
different stages
of design, right?

00:33:31.750 --> 00:33:36.282
There's a conceptual design,
where you just decide roughly

00:33:36.282 --> 00:33:37.490
what the thing's going to be.

00:33:37.490 --> 00:33:39.480
There's embodiment,
where you work out

00:33:39.480 --> 00:33:43.310
a lot of the more details.

00:33:43.310 --> 00:33:46.380
You design one version of it.

00:33:46.380 --> 00:33:48.340
And then there's the
detailed design, where

00:33:48.340 --> 00:33:50.770
you do all the fine-tuning.

00:33:50.770 --> 00:33:53.310
You do all the
final design things.

00:33:53.310 --> 00:33:55.030
And before you really
start your design,

00:33:55.030 --> 00:33:57.071
if you were going to design
an engineering thing,

00:33:57.071 --> 00:33:59.540
you would first of all think
about what's the market.

00:33:59.540 --> 00:34:02.349
And if you're writing, the
market is your readers.

00:34:02.349 --> 00:34:04.640
And so when you think about
what you're going to write,

00:34:04.640 --> 00:34:06.598
you have to think about
who's going to read it.

00:34:06.598 --> 00:34:08.820
And it's the same thing
when I give a talk.

00:34:08.820 --> 00:34:12.560
When I give a talk, before I
make a single PowerPoint slide,

00:34:12.560 --> 00:34:14.940
the first thing I think
about is who am I talking to

00:34:14.940 --> 00:34:16.690
and what do they already know?

00:34:16.690 --> 00:34:18.530
What's the audience?

00:34:18.530 --> 00:34:20.760
What are they looking
to get out of the talk?

00:34:20.760 --> 00:34:23.174
What am I trying to
convey in the talk?

00:34:23.174 --> 00:34:24.590
And the writing
is the same thing.

00:34:24.590 --> 00:34:26.469
You have to think
about your audience.

00:34:26.469 --> 00:34:30.590
So for instance, I
have technical talks.

00:34:30.590 --> 00:34:33.440
Obviously, I go give
technical talks at meetings,

00:34:33.440 --> 00:34:35.010
but I do other
sorts of talks too.

00:34:35.010 --> 00:34:36.218
I've got the woodpecker talk.

00:34:36.218 --> 00:34:38.760
I go give the woodpecker
talk at the Mass Audubon.

00:34:38.760 --> 00:34:40.989
And people come to
listen to that talk who

00:34:40.989 --> 00:34:43.290
are interested in birds
but they're not engineers.

00:34:43.290 --> 00:34:45.040
So when I do that
talk, I have to make it

00:34:45.040 --> 00:34:48.120
so somebody could understand
it who's intelligent

00:34:48.120 --> 00:34:49.889
but they're not
necessarily an engineer.

00:34:49.889 --> 00:34:51.530
So I give a different
kind of talk

00:34:51.530 --> 00:34:54.590
when I do that than when I
give an engineering talk.

00:34:54.590 --> 00:34:57.440
And I got invited
to a student dinner.

00:34:57.440 --> 00:35:00.960
I'm going out to somewhere
with some students on Friday.

00:35:00.960 --> 00:35:03.260
I'm going to give that how
I became a professor talk,

00:35:03.260 --> 00:35:06.020
and when I do the how I
became a professor talk,

00:35:06.020 --> 00:35:10.290
it's more general, and so it's
a different audience that I'm

00:35:10.290 --> 00:35:11.650
thinking about.

00:35:11.650 --> 00:35:14.152
And in some ways,
when I do these talks,

00:35:14.152 --> 00:35:15.610
it can be the same
group of people,

00:35:15.610 --> 00:35:17.600
but depending on what
I'm talking about,

00:35:17.600 --> 00:35:20.250
the way they look at
it is different, OK?

00:35:20.250 --> 00:35:22.600
So the market thing is
something to think about.

00:35:22.600 --> 00:35:25.530
So if you're writing
a thesis, your market

00:35:25.530 --> 00:35:28.560
is your PhD committee, who's
going to read the thesis

00:35:28.560 --> 00:35:30.020
and examine you on the thesis.

00:35:30.020 --> 00:35:31.827
If you're writing
a paper, you've

00:35:31.827 --> 00:35:33.410
got to think about
the market as being

00:35:33.410 --> 00:35:35.537
other people in your
research field, some of who

00:35:35.537 --> 00:35:37.620
are going to be the
reviewers, who are going to be

00:35:37.620 --> 00:35:39.890
reading it and criticizing it.

00:35:39.890 --> 00:35:44.020
If you're writing a general
popular science book,

00:35:44.020 --> 00:35:45.440
it's a different
kind of audience.

00:35:45.440 --> 00:35:49.600
If you're writing a
research proposal,

00:35:49.600 --> 00:35:51.964
the audience is going to
be the funding agency.

00:35:51.964 --> 00:35:54.380
Are they interested in what
you're talking about, but also

00:35:54.380 --> 00:35:56.700
reviewers, who are
going to be deciding

00:35:56.700 --> 00:35:58.800
whether or not to
give you the money

00:35:58.800 --> 00:36:00.836
and what the criticisms are.

00:36:00.836 --> 00:36:02.710
So you have to think
about who the market is.

00:36:02.710 --> 00:36:04.670
So that's one thing.

00:36:04.670 --> 00:36:08.164
And one thing that think about
in doing the writing-- you

00:36:08.164 --> 00:36:10.330
know Mike and I have written
several books together,

00:36:10.330 --> 00:36:12.329
and when I tell my neighbors
I've written books,

00:36:12.329 --> 00:36:14.350
they somehow think--
their first idea is

00:36:14.350 --> 00:36:16.265
that we start on
page one and we start

00:36:16.265 --> 00:36:17.890
writing the book from
page one and then

00:36:17.890 --> 00:36:20.176
we work our way
through to page 500.

00:36:20.176 --> 00:36:22.140
And that's not how
we do it at all

00:36:22.140 --> 00:36:24.134
and that's not how
I write papers.

00:36:24.134 --> 00:36:25.800
That's not how most
people write papers.

00:36:25.800 --> 00:36:29.060
You've got to think
about the big picture

00:36:29.060 --> 00:36:32.080
and think about,
roughly, what goes where.

00:36:32.080 --> 00:36:33.890
And then maybe
think about a draft

00:36:33.890 --> 00:36:37.190
that gets the
scientific facts right.

00:36:37.190 --> 00:36:40.690
You put the information
down, and then you

00:36:40.690 --> 00:36:44.180
try to figure out about how do
you make the style really nice?

00:36:44.180 --> 00:36:45.230
How to make it read well?

00:36:45.230 --> 00:36:47.444
How do you make it
easy to understand?

00:36:47.444 --> 00:36:49.610
How does one paragraph lead
into the next paragraph?

00:36:49.610 --> 00:36:51.070
So it's an iterative thing.

00:36:51.070 --> 00:36:53.660
It's not like you start
at page one or line one

00:36:53.660 --> 00:36:55.210
and you just start writing.

00:36:55.210 --> 00:36:58.710
So it's an iterative process,
the same as engineering design

00:36:58.710 --> 00:37:00.150
is an iterative process.

00:37:00.150 --> 00:37:04.340
If you were going to
design, I don't know,

00:37:04.340 --> 00:37:06.960
a skateboard or something,
you wouldn't just

00:37:06.960 --> 00:37:09.290
think you were going to make
one and that would be it.

00:37:09.290 --> 00:37:12.920
That's how writing is, and
often, students don't see it

00:37:12.920 --> 00:37:15.020
as this iterative thing.

00:37:15.020 --> 00:37:17.970
OK, so that's that page there.

00:37:17.970 --> 00:37:19.700
Let's see, I already
talked about market.

00:37:19.700 --> 00:37:22.590
I think I have another
little slide about-- here's

00:37:22.590 --> 00:37:24.880
another slide here
about markets.

00:37:24.880 --> 00:37:26.390
So this is what I just said.

00:37:26.390 --> 00:37:27.280
Who are the readers?

00:37:27.280 --> 00:37:28.535
How are they going to use it?

00:37:28.535 --> 00:37:30.660
So you've got to think
about who you're writing for

00:37:30.660 --> 00:37:36.240
or if you're giving a talk,
who's going to look at that.

00:37:36.240 --> 00:37:39.570
OK, now the next
phase is to make what

00:37:39.570 --> 00:37:42.370
Mike calls a concept sheet.

00:37:42.370 --> 00:37:45.230
I would just think of
this as an outline.

00:37:45.230 --> 00:37:47.620
And I always make
some sort of outline

00:37:47.620 --> 00:37:49.430
before I try to write anything.

00:37:49.430 --> 00:37:52.410
And there's different
ways you can do that.

00:37:52.410 --> 00:37:54.160
The thing that Mike's
got here and there's

00:37:54.160 --> 00:37:56.570
a nice little figure
on page six, which

00:37:56.570 --> 00:38:00.260
is what I've got up here, is
he takes a big piece of paper.

00:38:00.260 --> 00:38:02.930
In Europe, it would
be known as the A3.

00:38:02.930 --> 00:38:05.960
Here it would be known as
the eight and a half by 17.

00:38:05.960 --> 00:38:08.450
You take a big piece of paper.

00:38:08.450 --> 00:38:10.390
This stationery company
actually makes paper

00:38:10.390 --> 00:38:12.814
with big blank space in
the middle and little note

00:38:12.814 --> 00:38:15.230
space on the outside or you
could just use the back of it.

00:38:15.230 --> 00:38:17.150
So you take a big
piece of paper and you

00:38:17.150 --> 00:38:19.780
may think this is douffy,
but it actually helps.

00:38:19.780 --> 00:38:21.370
So you take your
big piece of paper,

00:38:21.370 --> 00:38:23.739
and you just make
boxes about each topic.

00:38:23.739 --> 00:38:25.280
You're going to have
an introduction,

00:38:25.280 --> 00:38:27.071
you're going to have
methods and materials,

00:38:27.071 --> 00:38:28.730
you're going to have
a result section.

00:38:28.730 --> 00:38:32.680
And you think about what should
go into each of those boxes.

00:38:32.680 --> 00:38:34.350
And what you're
trying to do here

00:38:34.350 --> 00:38:36.812
is think about the whole paper
and how it all fits together

00:38:36.812 --> 00:38:39.020
and what goes where and what
are you going to include

00:38:39.020 --> 00:38:40.890
and what are you not
going to include.

00:38:40.890 --> 00:38:43.380
So people think about writing
as sitting at the keyboard

00:38:43.380 --> 00:38:47.035
and typing, but
that's just the--

00:38:47.035 --> 00:38:48.660
how when you get a
problem on a problem

00:38:48.660 --> 00:38:51.610
set, you turn and crank, that's
the turning and cranking part.

00:38:51.610 --> 00:38:55.900
The thoughtful part is
figuring out what to put in,

00:38:55.900 --> 00:38:58.040
what to leave out,
what figures you want,

00:38:58.040 --> 00:38:59.490
how you organize
the whole thing,

00:38:59.490 --> 00:39:02.410
how you put it all together,
and this helps you do that.

00:39:02.410 --> 00:39:06.130
And you can make this--
it's just for you.

00:39:06.130 --> 00:39:07.950
It doesn't have to look great.

00:39:07.950 --> 00:39:09.450
You can make this
messy if you want.

00:39:09.450 --> 00:39:10.520
It doesn't really matter.

00:39:10.520 --> 00:39:14.079
But it's good to have some sort
of an overview of how you want

00:39:14.079 --> 00:39:15.620
to put the thing
together, and that's

00:39:15.620 --> 00:39:18.670
what this stage helps you do.

00:39:18.670 --> 00:39:21.630
So Mike's put other
little things here.

00:39:21.630 --> 00:39:24.910
So see papers by
so-and-so and so-and-so.

00:39:24.910 --> 00:39:26.216
So you've got an introduction.

00:39:26.216 --> 00:39:27.590
You want to talk
about something.

00:39:27.590 --> 00:39:29.780
You know there should be
some references go here.

00:39:29.780 --> 00:39:31.655
Maybe you think there's
some extra references

00:39:31.655 --> 00:39:33.237
you haven't got.

00:39:33.237 --> 00:39:34.820
Maybe something in
the method, there's

00:39:34.820 --> 00:39:36.686
some analogy you can use here.

00:39:36.686 --> 00:39:38.560
Maybe you need a figure,
needs a good figure.

00:39:38.560 --> 00:39:40.270
You don't have to
actually have the figure.

00:39:40.270 --> 00:39:42.728
You just say I need a figure
and you have a vague idea what

00:39:42.728 --> 00:39:44.500
the figure looks like.

00:39:44.500 --> 00:39:46.490
Here there's some
discussion point.

00:39:46.490 --> 00:39:50.230
Discuss this with collaborators,
Ed, all this stuff.

00:39:50.230 --> 00:39:53.890
So you just put down roughly
what needs to go where

00:39:53.890 --> 00:39:55.420
and you think about
the whole thing

00:39:55.420 --> 00:39:57.500
and how it's all
going to fit together.

00:39:57.500 --> 00:40:01.870
And then as you work through
it, it looks more like this.

00:40:01.870 --> 00:40:03.255
So this would be on page seven.

00:40:06.220 --> 00:40:09.940
And this is filled
in, and if fact,

00:40:09.940 --> 00:40:12.730
this particular one, what
he's written down here

00:40:12.730 --> 00:40:17.550
is the overview he made for
making this booklet, OK?

00:40:17.550 --> 00:40:19.700
So the things
refer to this book.

00:40:19.700 --> 00:40:21.454
So here's the introduction.

00:40:21.454 --> 00:40:23.620
Here's the little chart we
went through and through,

00:40:23.620 --> 00:40:26.470
the concept design, embodiment,
and detail, blah, blah, blah.

00:40:26.470 --> 00:40:27.900
Here's the need,
the market need.

00:40:27.900 --> 00:40:29.407
We just talked about that.

00:40:29.407 --> 00:40:31.990
Here's the concept thing that
we we're just talking about now.

00:40:31.990 --> 00:40:35.240
Then we're going to talk about
each of these different phases.

00:40:35.240 --> 00:40:39.550
And his initials are
MFA, Michael F. Ashby.

00:40:39.550 --> 00:40:41.580
Think out, that means
think about this more.

00:40:41.580 --> 00:40:43.040
I haven't figured this out yet.

00:40:43.040 --> 00:40:46.680
I need an example here,
all these kinds of things.

00:40:46.680 --> 00:40:48.330
So this is the way he does it.

00:40:48.330 --> 00:40:50.230
There's a couple of
other ways you can do it.

00:40:50.230 --> 00:40:53.200
One way is to just make
a bullet outline, that's

00:40:53.200 --> 00:40:54.294
typically what I do.

00:40:54.294 --> 00:40:56.210
You know you're going
to have an introduction,

00:40:56.210 --> 00:40:57.480
these different headings.

00:40:57.480 --> 00:40:59.460
And you might put in
the bullet outline

00:40:59.460 --> 00:41:02.180
these same sorts of things,
like I need this figure

00:41:02.180 --> 00:41:04.560
or we need to get
one more set of data

00:41:04.560 --> 00:41:06.800
or I need to look
up this reference.

00:41:06.800 --> 00:41:08.990
So it doesn't have
to be finished,

00:41:08.990 --> 00:41:11.510
but it's a thing that tells
you what have you got,

00:41:11.510 --> 00:41:14.540
what do you need to do to
make it all come together.

00:41:14.540 --> 00:41:16.570
So that's one way to do it.

00:41:16.570 --> 00:41:18.680
Another way to do it is
by thinking about what

00:41:18.680 --> 00:41:20.540
figures you want in the paper.

00:41:20.540 --> 00:41:23.860
So some people, before
they write any words,

00:41:23.860 --> 00:41:26.520
they say, well, I know I
want to have these figures,

00:41:26.520 --> 00:41:29.060
and then they build the
words around the figures.

00:41:29.060 --> 00:41:32.560
And they can even sketch
out what the figures are.

00:41:32.560 --> 00:41:34.769
Some people even start before
they start the project,

00:41:34.769 --> 00:41:36.185
they say what kind
of figures do I

00:41:36.185 --> 00:41:37.480
want at the end of the project?

00:41:37.480 --> 00:41:39.390
And they don't know if the data
is going to do this or that.

00:41:39.390 --> 00:41:40.970
They don't know which way
the data is going to go,

00:41:40.970 --> 00:41:42.920
but they say I want
to have a plot of one

00:41:42.920 --> 00:41:44.525
thing versus another thing.

00:41:44.525 --> 00:41:47.619
Oh, you're looking
like this is not OK?

00:41:47.619 --> 00:41:48.160
AUDIENCE: No.

00:41:48.160 --> 00:41:48.868
LORNA GIBSON: No?

00:41:48.868 --> 00:41:51.550
OK, yeah, some people do this.

00:41:51.550 --> 00:41:54.320
So even when you're
ready to write,

00:41:54.320 --> 00:41:57.130
you could say to yourself,
well, in the methods,

00:41:57.130 --> 00:42:00.380
do I need a figure that's a
schematic of some apparatus?

00:42:00.380 --> 00:42:03.530
In the results, how am I
going to present the results

00:42:03.530 --> 00:42:04.280
in the discussion?

00:42:04.280 --> 00:42:05.920
Do we need some
other kind of figure?

00:42:05.920 --> 00:42:07.890
So if you have a
set of figures, you

00:42:07.890 --> 00:42:10.535
can work the text
around those figures.

00:42:10.535 --> 00:42:12.960
So that's another
way to do this.

00:42:12.960 --> 00:42:15.690
So those are just three
options, but all of them

00:42:15.690 --> 00:42:19.140
have in common that you
think about the whole paper

00:42:19.140 --> 00:42:20.690
and how it all fits
together and what

00:42:20.690 --> 00:42:22.520
goes where and what
do you have already

00:42:22.520 --> 00:42:25.400
and what else do
you need to get, OK?

00:42:25.400 --> 00:42:27.230
So that's that.

00:42:27.230 --> 00:42:29.170
And then what I
was going to do--

00:42:29.170 --> 00:42:31.815
I think that's probably the
last figure that's-- yeah, OK.

00:42:31.815 --> 00:42:33.440
So there's just this
little thing here.

00:42:33.440 --> 00:42:35.481
So what I was going to do
is just talk about some

00:42:35.481 --> 00:42:37.780
of the other things in
this little booklet that

00:42:37.780 --> 00:42:42.780
work through each of these
stages of the writing.

00:42:42.780 --> 00:42:45.437
So that's the concept,
and then the next phase

00:42:45.437 --> 00:42:47.020
would be what's
called the embodiment,

00:42:47.020 --> 00:42:49.350
if you think of the
design language,

00:42:49.350 --> 00:42:51.090
and that would be
the first draft.

00:42:51.090 --> 00:42:53.970
And I think most people find
the most difficult thing is

00:42:53.970 --> 00:42:55.120
to write the first draft.

00:42:55.120 --> 00:42:56.460
I mean, I find that the hardest.

00:42:56.460 --> 00:42:58.300
Once you've got
something, editing it

00:42:58.300 --> 00:43:00.270
is relatively straightforward.

00:43:00.270 --> 00:43:02.230
You go, oh, this piece
should go over there

00:43:02.230 --> 00:43:04.240
or there's something missing.

00:43:04.240 --> 00:43:07.350
But getting the first draft
down is the hardest thing.

00:43:07.350 --> 00:43:12.200
And one of the
things-- it's like when

00:43:12.200 --> 00:43:14.590
I talked about
writing the book, you

00:43:14.590 --> 00:43:16.730
don't write the draft
sequentially either.

00:43:16.730 --> 00:43:19.020
I typically tell students
to start with the materials

00:43:19.020 --> 00:43:21.145
and methods because that's
the most straightforward

00:43:21.145 --> 00:43:22.874
and it's the easiest to write.

00:43:22.874 --> 00:43:25.290
There's not a whole lot of
mystery to how you actually did

00:43:25.290 --> 00:43:26.770
something you've already done.

00:43:26.770 --> 00:43:29.310
So I tell people don't write
the introduction first.

00:43:29.310 --> 00:43:32.300
That's a bad idea because
it's actually often not

00:43:32.300 --> 00:43:33.930
so easy to write
the introduction.

00:43:33.930 --> 00:43:36.970
So I tell people to write the
materials and methods first.

00:43:36.970 --> 00:43:40.230
Write the result section
because you've got your results

00:43:40.230 --> 00:43:42.390
and you know what the
results are going to be.

00:43:42.390 --> 00:43:43.960
So those are the
two easiest things.

00:43:43.960 --> 00:43:46.570
And often, I think,
what people find

00:43:46.570 --> 00:43:49.755
is if they find it hard to write
it's because they don't know

00:43:49.755 --> 00:43:52.380
what they want to write or they
haven't thought things through.

00:43:52.380 --> 00:43:54.270
They haven't got their
thoughts together.

00:43:54.270 --> 00:43:56.350
And if you've got
your thoughts, if you

00:43:56.350 --> 00:44:01.490
know what you want to say, then
the writing becomes easier.

00:44:01.490 --> 00:44:03.740
So one of the pieces
of advice Mike

00:44:03.740 --> 00:44:06.890
gave me, and it's
in this booklet too,

00:44:06.890 --> 00:44:09.580
is in the first draft
what you should try to do

00:44:09.580 --> 00:44:11.240
is just get the facts down.

00:44:11.240 --> 00:44:13.180
Just get the information
down and don't

00:44:13.180 --> 00:44:14.994
worry about if it
doesn't sound quite right

00:44:14.994 --> 00:44:17.160
or if this sentence doesn't
lead into that sentence.

00:44:17.160 --> 00:44:19.230
Don't worry about the
style of it at all.

00:44:19.230 --> 00:44:20.710
Just try to get the facts down.

00:44:20.710 --> 00:44:22.430
Just try to get the
information down.

00:44:22.430 --> 00:44:24.290
And once you've
got the information

00:44:24.290 --> 00:44:27.120
and you've got some kind
of framework-- I'm not

00:44:27.120 --> 00:44:30.000
saying that you don't want
to make the style good,

00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:32.940
you do, but you don't need
to do that the first thing.

00:44:32.940 --> 00:44:35.190
The first thing is just
to get the facts down,

00:44:35.190 --> 00:44:38.080
and then you can
edit it later on.

00:44:38.080 --> 00:44:40.830
It's more of this
iterative process.

00:44:40.830 --> 00:44:43.000
OK, so the first draft,
the most important thing

00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:44.482
is just to get the facts down.

00:44:44.482 --> 00:44:46.440
Then, I'm not going to
read all of these things

00:44:46.440 --> 00:44:49.400
because you can just
read them yourself,

00:44:49.400 --> 00:44:51.219
but I'll just comment
on a few things.

00:44:51.219 --> 00:44:53.135
So one thing he's got--
I'm on page eight now,

00:44:53.135 --> 00:44:55.930
is the abstract.

00:44:55.930 --> 00:44:57.790
So the abstract
should be concise.

00:44:57.790 --> 00:45:01.521
It should be fairly
short and you

00:45:01.521 --> 00:45:03.520
want to tell people why
you're doing what you're

00:45:03.520 --> 00:45:06.400
doing, what you did,
what the key result is,

00:45:06.400 --> 00:45:07.710
and what the conclusions are.

00:45:07.710 --> 00:45:10.950
So it can be pretty short.

00:45:10.950 --> 00:45:12.760
There's a section
on the introduction.

00:45:12.760 --> 00:45:14.316
You can just read that.

00:45:14.316 --> 00:45:15.810
Let's see here.

00:45:15.810 --> 00:45:18.450
Yeah, I think, you can read
yourself these other things.

00:45:18.450 --> 00:45:20.241
I don't want to go
through the whole thing.

00:45:22.860 --> 00:45:24.980
All right, so that's that.

00:45:24.980 --> 00:45:28.610
OK, so you get to the
end of the first draft,

00:45:28.610 --> 00:45:30.710
there's a little
section on figures here.

00:45:30.710 --> 00:45:32.835
Let me just make some
comments on that.

00:45:35.570 --> 00:45:37.530
People who are busy
and may not want

00:45:37.530 --> 00:45:39.610
to read every word
that you've written

00:45:39.610 --> 00:45:42.160
will look at the figures, and
they'll look at the figures

00:45:42.160 --> 00:45:44.244
to make some judgment about
does this look useful?

00:45:44.244 --> 00:45:45.910
Does this look like
you've got something

00:45:45.910 --> 00:45:47.260
I want to spend more time on?

00:45:47.260 --> 00:45:52.040
So it's important to make the
figures easily understandable

00:45:52.040 --> 00:45:55.130
and to be fairly self-contained.

00:45:55.130 --> 00:45:57.989
So you want to make
the figures clear.

00:45:57.989 --> 00:46:00.030
You don't want to have
too much information on it

00:46:00.030 --> 00:46:02.211
so that people can't
follow what's going on,

00:46:02.211 --> 00:46:03.960
and you want them to
illustrate the points

00:46:03.960 --> 00:46:05.680
that you're trying to make.

00:46:05.680 --> 00:46:08.120
So the figures are
very important.

00:46:08.120 --> 00:46:11.140
And then when you've got
the first draft finished,

00:46:11.140 --> 00:46:15.000
the next step, which I
find tremendously useful

00:46:15.000 --> 00:46:18.210
and students often don't
get that this is a step.

00:46:18.210 --> 00:46:19.760
The next step is
you put it somewhere

00:46:19.760 --> 00:46:22.099
and you don't do anything
with it for a while.

00:46:22.099 --> 00:46:24.140
And this is why it's
important not to write it up

00:46:24.140 --> 00:46:25.640
at the last second.

00:46:25.640 --> 00:46:29.250
Because there's something
about, you work on something,

00:46:29.250 --> 00:46:31.300
you put it to one
side, you don't do it.

00:46:31.300 --> 00:46:33.285
You just leave it and
you go do something else.

00:46:33.285 --> 00:46:35.410
And then when you come back
to it, all of a sudden,

00:46:35.410 --> 00:46:38.830
you see things that you didn't
see the first time through.

00:46:38.830 --> 00:46:40.940
So the next step is you
just put it to one side

00:46:40.940 --> 00:46:42.100
for a couple days.

00:46:42.100 --> 00:46:44.070
But you can only do
that step for a class

00:46:44.070 --> 00:46:47.534
if you started before the
night before it's due, OK?

00:46:47.534 --> 00:46:49.200
So that's why you
have to start earlier.

00:46:49.200 --> 00:46:52.530
That's why I'm telling
you this now, OK?

00:46:52.530 --> 00:46:54.960
So you put it aside and then
you go have a cup of coffee.

00:46:54.960 --> 00:46:56.543
You see there's
several cups of coffee

00:46:56.543 --> 00:46:59.180
that Mike has happily
drawn for us here.

00:46:59.180 --> 00:47:01.270
OK, then the next
part of this is

00:47:01.270 --> 00:47:03.300
all about grammar and
sentence structure.

00:47:03.300 --> 00:47:04.550
I'm not going to go over that.

00:47:04.550 --> 00:47:05.999
You can read all that yourself.

00:47:05.999 --> 00:47:08.040
But there is one amusing
thing I want to tell you

00:47:08.040 --> 00:47:09.690
because there's a cute story.

00:47:09.690 --> 00:47:10.940
I'm on page 16 now.

00:47:10.940 --> 00:47:12.750
There's a thing about spelling.

00:47:12.750 --> 00:47:14.610
Mike is a terrible speller.

00:47:14.610 --> 00:47:16.470
When I was his student,
he used to-- there

00:47:16.470 --> 00:47:18.030
were no word processors.

00:47:18.030 --> 00:47:21.159
And we used to write things
and he would write things

00:47:21.159 --> 00:47:22.950
and I would say, I
can't read your writing.

00:47:22.950 --> 00:47:25.116
And he says, ah, well, I
make up for my bad spelling

00:47:25.116 --> 00:47:27.120
with my bad writing.

00:47:27.120 --> 00:47:29.400
So I couldn't tell if he
had spelled something right.

00:47:29.400 --> 00:47:32.500
The other thing we
found was that, we

00:47:32.500 --> 00:47:34.600
wrote the cellular solid
book, the first edition

00:47:34.600 --> 00:47:36.700
was in the 1980s.

00:47:36.700 --> 00:47:39.320
And I grew up in Canada,
then I lived in England,

00:47:39.320 --> 00:47:40.450
then I moved here.

00:47:40.450 --> 00:47:43.610
He grew up in Australia,
then he moved to England,

00:47:43.610 --> 00:47:46.030
then he moved to the States
then he moved back to England.

00:47:46.030 --> 00:47:49.050
And words that end, that
we spell I-Z-E, like

00:47:49.050 --> 00:47:51.720
normalized, like
normalized variables.

00:47:51.720 --> 00:47:55.730
They're I-Z-E here.

00:47:55.730 --> 00:47:58.050
In England, they're all I-S-E.

00:47:58.050 --> 00:48:00.710
OK, and then some of
the words, it turns out,

00:48:00.710 --> 00:48:04.580
Canadians spell with an
I-Z-E and some with I-S-E.

00:48:04.580 --> 00:48:06.990
So anyway, we wrote the
entire fricking book.

00:48:06.990 --> 00:48:09.120
We were almost ready
to send it off,

00:48:09.120 --> 00:48:11.850
and we have all those graphs
where the axes are normalized,

00:48:11.850 --> 00:48:16.710
and we must have used the word
normalized like 100 times,

00:48:16.710 --> 00:48:19.140
and we realized half the
time we had spelled it I-S-E

00:48:19.140 --> 00:48:21.091
and half the time we
had spelled it I-Z-E.

00:48:21.091 --> 00:48:23.590
And then we had to go back and
find them all and fix it all.

00:48:23.590 --> 00:48:28.230
So anyway, that's just our
little story about spelling.

00:48:28.230 --> 00:48:29.890
OK, there's a thing
about punctuation.

00:48:29.890 --> 00:48:30.639
You can read that.

00:48:30.639 --> 00:48:32.040
That's kind of boring.

00:48:32.040 --> 00:48:34.350
I wanted to move on to
the bit about style,

00:48:34.350 --> 00:48:37.480
because style is important too.

00:48:37.480 --> 00:48:41.060
And people remember papers
that are well written.

00:48:41.060 --> 00:48:45.450
Obviously, papers that have
valuable scientific information

00:48:45.450 --> 00:48:48.150
are memorable too, but
if it's well-written,

00:48:48.150 --> 00:48:52.020
it's more memorable, and the
style really is important.

00:48:52.020 --> 00:48:54.330
And it's the same
with giving a talk.

00:48:54.330 --> 00:48:56.670
You can convey the
same information,

00:48:56.670 --> 00:49:01.160
but if you don't have it
presented in a clear way,

00:49:01.160 --> 00:49:03.180
people aren't going
to remember it.

00:49:03.180 --> 00:49:04.960
So the first rule--
so I'm on page 20.

00:49:04.960 --> 00:49:07.360
The first rule,
now, is to be clear.

00:49:07.360 --> 00:49:12.790
And being clear, it doesn't mean
having long-winded sentences

00:49:12.790 --> 00:49:14.050
with lots of jargon.

00:49:14.050 --> 00:49:17.710
It really just means make
it short, make it concise,

00:49:17.710 --> 00:49:19.790
make it clear what
you want to say.

00:49:19.790 --> 00:49:21.360
So Mike has several
examples here

00:49:21.360 --> 00:49:23.680
of headlines from
the newspapers, which

00:49:23.680 --> 00:49:24.840
were not clear.

00:49:24.840 --> 00:49:27.310
So I'll just read these out
because I find them amusing.

00:49:27.310 --> 00:49:29.580
"Red Tape Holds Up New Bridge."

00:49:29.580 --> 00:49:32.630
So, OK, maybe the red tape
temporally held it up, but not

00:49:32.630 --> 00:49:34.000
spatially held it up.

00:49:34.000 --> 00:49:36.000
OK, and then here's another
one. "Something Went

00:49:36.000 --> 00:49:37.950
Wrong in Jet Crash,
Expert Says."

00:49:37.950 --> 00:49:41.420
In fact, you hear this all
the time on the news now.

00:49:41.420 --> 00:49:42.900
Obviously, something went wrong.

00:49:42.900 --> 00:49:45.233
You don't have to be an
engineer to figure out something

00:49:45.233 --> 00:49:46.570
went wrong in a jet crash.

00:49:46.570 --> 00:49:49.930
Then, "Chef Throws Heart In
To Help Feed the Hungry."

00:49:49.930 --> 00:49:53.560
OK, well, maybe that's
a little too much.

00:49:53.560 --> 00:49:56.480
This is my favorite one,
"Prostitutes Appeal to Pope."

00:49:56.480 --> 00:49:58.385
OK, there's different
ways you can appeal.

00:50:01.630 --> 00:50:04.420
You don't have to appeal
to the Pope in that way.

00:50:04.420 --> 00:50:06.859
And then, "Panda Mating
Fails, Vet Takes Over."

00:50:06.859 --> 00:50:09.150
I don't think the vet really
took over with the mating,

00:50:09.150 --> 00:50:11.250
but you know what they mean.

00:50:11.250 --> 00:50:15.480
OK, so one thing is clarity.

00:50:15.480 --> 00:50:17.510
Another point is don't waffle.

00:50:17.510 --> 00:50:20.640
You want things to be
concise and get to the point.

00:50:20.640 --> 00:50:23.780
So he's got this
example here from what

00:50:23.780 --> 00:50:27.490
he cites as a well-known but
anonymous materials text.

00:50:27.490 --> 00:50:29.140
"The selection of
the proper material

00:50:29.140 --> 00:50:30.960
is a key step in
the design process,

00:50:30.960 --> 00:50:32.830
because it is the
crucial decision that

00:50:32.830 --> 00:50:35.270
links computer
calculations and the lines

00:50:35.270 --> 00:50:37.890
on an engineering drawing with
a real or working design."

00:50:37.890 --> 00:50:39.414
But what does it say?

00:50:39.414 --> 00:50:41.080
It says material
selection is important.

00:50:41.080 --> 00:50:44.170
So don't say something
in some long-winded way

00:50:44.170 --> 00:50:46.830
that you could say
in a short way.

00:50:46.830 --> 00:50:48.290
OK, let's see.

00:50:51.190 --> 00:50:53.450
So let me move on
to the next page.

00:50:53.450 --> 00:50:55.900
The next step that I-- let
me emphasize one more time,

00:50:55.900 --> 00:50:59.620
is 8.5, revise and rewrite.

00:50:59.620 --> 00:51:02.934
So writing really is iterative.

00:51:02.934 --> 00:51:05.350
Those books that you've seen
that Mike and I have written,

00:51:05.350 --> 00:51:07.930
I cannot tell you how many
drafts of each chapter we went

00:51:07.930 --> 00:51:09.800
through over and
over and over again.

00:51:09.800 --> 00:51:16.080
So to make it good, you have
to do it over and over again.

00:51:16.080 --> 00:51:17.850
OK, there's that.

00:51:17.850 --> 00:51:18.350
Let me see.

00:51:18.350 --> 00:51:20.650
Is there anything
else I have here?

00:51:20.650 --> 00:51:23.020
Ah, here's a couple things
that are not so obvious.

00:51:23.020 --> 00:51:25.850
So one is, for each
paragraph you should

00:51:25.850 --> 00:51:27.870
have a good first sentence.

00:51:27.870 --> 00:51:29.400
You should tell the
reader something

00:51:29.400 --> 00:51:31.609
they don't already know.

00:51:31.609 --> 00:51:34.150
So there's some examples here,
and you can read through them.

00:51:34.150 --> 00:51:36.730
But it is really helpful
for each paragraph

00:51:36.730 --> 00:51:39.580
to have a good opening sentence.

00:51:39.580 --> 00:51:41.417
Another thing is at the
end of the paragraph

00:51:41.417 --> 00:51:44.000
it's good if there's a sentence
that links it to the next one.

00:51:44.000 --> 00:51:47.580
So it hints at what the next
paragraph's going to be about,

00:51:47.580 --> 00:51:49.310
so it leads the
reader through it,

00:51:49.310 --> 00:51:51.530
and it is a logical progression.

00:51:51.530 --> 00:51:53.320
So an opening sentence
for the paragraph

00:51:53.320 --> 00:51:55.500
and the final
sentence, you might

00:51:55.500 --> 00:51:57.947
want to look at in a
bit more gory detail.

00:51:57.947 --> 00:52:00.280
OK, and then there are some
references at the very back,

00:52:00.280 --> 00:52:02.430
at page 25.

00:52:02.430 --> 00:52:05.830
And I brought a couple of books
in that I have found helpful.

00:52:05.830 --> 00:52:07.310
So you may have seen these.

00:52:07.310 --> 00:52:10.260
One is called The
Elements of Style

00:52:10.260 --> 00:52:13.540
and this is by Strunk and
White, so William Strunk, Jr.

00:52:13.540 --> 00:52:14.760
and EB White.

00:52:14.760 --> 00:52:18.630
You guys know EB White,
Charlotte's Web, same guy.

00:52:18.630 --> 00:52:23.360
He's written this small, small,
not too long to have a look at

00:52:23.360 --> 00:52:25.010
book about style.

00:52:25.010 --> 00:52:30.610
So there's some rules of
usage, which is grammar stuff,

00:52:30.610 --> 00:52:33.090
but there's principles
of composition

00:52:33.090 --> 00:52:36.020
and there's a chapter called
"An Approach to Style."

00:52:36.020 --> 00:52:37.820
And so here's some
of the headings.

00:52:37.820 --> 00:52:39.630
Place yourself in
the background.

00:52:39.630 --> 00:52:41.320
Write in a way that
comes naturally.

00:52:41.320 --> 00:52:42.809
Work from a suitable design.

00:52:42.809 --> 00:52:45.100
These people are not engineers,
but they're saying work

00:52:45.100 --> 00:52:46.058
from a suitable design.

00:52:46.058 --> 00:52:47.980
It's like that concept thing.

00:52:47.980 --> 00:52:49.960
Revise and rewrite,
did I mention that,

00:52:49.960 --> 00:52:51.130
revise and rewrite?

00:52:51.130 --> 00:52:52.380
Do not overwrite.

00:52:52.380 --> 00:52:54.950
Don't make it too complicated.

00:52:54.950 --> 00:52:56.750
Avoid the use of qualifiers.

00:52:56.750 --> 00:52:59.204
If you say something's very
stiff, what does that mean?

00:52:59.204 --> 00:53:00.370
You can just say it's stiff.

00:53:00.370 --> 00:53:02.670
You don't have to
say it's very stiff.

00:53:02.670 --> 00:53:05.240
Very compared to what?

00:53:05.240 --> 00:53:06.120
Let's see.

00:53:06.120 --> 00:53:09.840
Use orthodox spelling, blah,
blah, blah, blah, blah.

00:53:09.840 --> 00:53:12.130
Avoid fancy words.

00:53:12.130 --> 00:53:14.630
OK, be clear, all
this kind of stuff.

00:53:14.630 --> 00:53:18.170
So Strunk and White
is old but good.

00:53:18.170 --> 00:53:21.450
And then, there's this
book here by Bill Bryson.

00:53:21.450 --> 00:53:24.160
Bryson's Dictionary
of Troublesome Words.

00:53:24.160 --> 00:53:26.490
So this is, it is
like a dictionary.

00:53:26.490 --> 00:53:30.250
It goes by letter and
has different words,

00:53:30.250 --> 00:53:32.430
but it talks about
how people sometimes

00:53:32.430 --> 00:53:35.000
use a word thinking it means
one thing when it doesn't, it

00:53:35.000 --> 00:53:36.590
actually means something else.

00:53:36.590 --> 00:53:40.880
And so it's just words
that people use commonly

00:53:40.880 --> 00:53:45.470
that they sometimes confuse
with what they really mean.

00:53:45.470 --> 00:53:47.820
So it's a very handy thing too.

00:53:47.820 --> 00:53:49.210
Do you know Bill Bryson?

00:53:49.210 --> 00:53:50.821
Very funny travel writer.

00:53:50.821 --> 00:53:53.070
If you ever go somewhere
that Bill Bryson has been you

00:53:53.070 --> 00:53:55.420
should get the book he's
written about it because he's

00:53:55.420 --> 00:53:56.830
very funny.

00:53:56.830 --> 00:53:58.145
OK, so I think that's it.

00:53:58.145 --> 00:54:00.270
Oh, and then, I think, the
very end of this booklet

00:54:00.270 --> 00:54:04.330
has some examples of good
writing and bad writing.

00:54:04.330 --> 00:54:07.510
So you can have a
look at that too.

00:54:07.510 --> 00:54:11.757
All right, so are we good
on how to write a paper?

00:54:11.757 --> 00:54:13.340
Do you have questions
on how to write?

00:54:13.340 --> 00:54:15.670
Writing is important.

00:54:15.670 --> 00:54:17.480
So I have one more
writing story.

00:54:17.480 --> 00:54:20.530
So when I first got this job at
MIT, I was living in Arlington,

00:54:20.530 --> 00:54:22.980
and my mom comes to
visit me from Toronto.

00:54:22.980 --> 00:54:25.900
And I'm work, work, work,
work, working, working,

00:54:25.900 --> 00:54:28.371
and my mom says to
me, she says, my, you

00:54:28.371 --> 00:54:29.745
spend a lot of
your life writing.

00:54:29.745 --> 00:54:32.040
I'm like, Mom, that's
what I get paid to do.

00:54:32.040 --> 00:54:34.640
I get paid to write.

00:54:34.640 --> 00:54:36.140
Like she always
thought I was should

00:54:36.140 --> 00:54:37.600
be spending maybe
30 hours a week

00:54:37.600 --> 00:54:38.980
lecturing or
something like that.

00:54:38.980 --> 00:54:40.355
Like she, well,
you're a teacher.

00:54:40.355 --> 00:54:42.810
You only teach three hours
a week, what is this?

00:54:42.810 --> 00:54:43.930
I'm like, I write, Mom.

00:54:43.930 --> 00:54:45.500
That's what I do.

00:54:45.500 --> 00:54:48.700
